subSection.paragraph:
Root nodule metabolism is highly specialized. Within the 

Alnus

infected cells, 

Frankia

is supplied with malate by the host plant (
Jeong et al., 2004
) and exports the fixed nitrogen to the cytosol in the form of ammonia (
Guan et al., 1996
). The exported ammonium is assimilated and transported to the xylem mainly in the form of citrulline (
Valverde and Huss-Danell, 2008
). Citrulline is the main amino acid found in roots and nodules (
Brooks and Benson, 2016
; 
Hay et al., 2020
). Altogether, the primary metabolism in nodules is well known, while the specialized metabolites in actinorhizal nodules have yet to be characterized. As part of our ongoing phytochemical research on root nodules to provide chemical understanding of actinorhizal symbiosis (
Jin et al., 2021
), we investigated the constituents of 

A. cremastogyne

root nodules and identified four 3-pentanol glycosides, including three undescribed ones. In addition, the distribution of 3-pentanol glycosides was studied.

The seventeen known compounds were identified as 3-pentyl 
β
-D- glucopyranoside (1) (
Guchhait and Misra, 2011
), 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutarate (5) (
Fujioka et al., 1989
), germacrene B (6) (
Piet et al., 1995
), 2-phenylethyl D- rutinoside (7) (
Umehara et al., 1988
), 
β
-sitosterol (8) (
Danelutte et al., 2005
), taraxerone (9) (
Sakurai et al., 1987
; 
Zhou et al., 2007
), lupenone (10) (
Pereira et al., 1996
), lupeol (11) (
Cao et al., 2017
), 22-hydroxyhopane (12) (
Ageta et al., 1993
), bacteriohopanetetrol (13) (
Costantino et al., 2000
), 1,7-bis(4-hydroxyphenyl)-4-hepten-3-one (14) (Chen, J. et al., 1998), 5 
S
-hydroxy-3-platyphyllone (15) (Li, J. et al., 2012; 
Smite et al., 1993
), platyphyllone 5 
S
-glucoside (16) (
Smite et al., 1993
), (5 
S
)-1-(4-hydroxyphenyl)-7-(3,4-dihydroxyphenyl)-5- 
O -β
-D- glucopyranosyl-heptan-3-one (17) (Novakovic´et al., 2013), (
S
)-1, 7-bis-(4-hydroxyphenyl)-heptan-3-one-5- 
O -β
-D- xylopyranoside (18) (Chen, J. et al., 2000), alnuside 
A
(19) (
Kuroyanagi et al., 2005
), and alnuside B (20) (
Kuroyanagi et al., 2005
) (
Fig. S3
), by comparison of spectroscopic data with values reported in the literature. Although 3-pentyl 
β
-D- glucopyranoside (1) is a known compound, it was previously reported only as an artificially synthesised molecule (
Guchhait and Misra, 2011
). The natural occurrence of 3-pentanol glycosides is here reported for the first time to the best of our knowledge. Besides 3-pentanol glycosides, the main components in root nodules of 

A. cremastogyne

are diarylheptanoids, which are characteristic components of alder plants (
Ibrahim et al., 2016
; 
Ilic-Tomic et al., 2017
; 
Saxena et al., 2016
; 
Sung and Lee, 2015
). Compounds 8–11 and 14–20 isolated in this study from 

A. cremastogyne

root nodules, have been also reported in other 

Alnus
species

(
Ren et al., 2017
), and are assumed to be of plant origin. Bacteriohopanetetrol (13) is a bacterial hopanoid, which has been abundantly found in 

Alnus

nodules (
Berry et al., 1991
). The phytosterol 
β
-sitosterol (8), taraxerone (9), 22-hydroxyhopane (12), lupenone (10) and lupeol (11) representing lupane-type triterpenes, were also isolated from root nodules of actinorhizal 

Casuarina equisetifolia
(
Jin et al., 2021
)

.

After sulfuric acid hydrolysis of 

A. cremastogyne

leaves, stems, fruits, root nodules, and roots, 3-pentanol was quantified by gas chromatography mass spectrometry (GC-MS) as total content. The content of free 3- pentanol was also quantified in the samples without sulfuric acid hydrolysis, of which the results are shown in 
Fig. 3A
. The content of free 3- pentanol in root nodules and roots were 9.5 and 0.8 μmol/g (
FW
), respectively, while it was not detected in leaves, stems and fruits. The difference values between the total and free content indicated the content of 3-pentanol released from glycosides, which could be featured as the content of 3-pentanol glycosides. The results are shown in 
Fig. 3B
. The content of 3-pentanol glycosides varied greatly among the different organs. The contents of 3-pentanol glycosides in leaves, stems, fruits, root nodules, and roots were 1.0 μmol/g (
FW
), 3.5 μmol/g (
FW
), 0 μmol/ g (
FW
), 120.7 μmol/g (
FW
), and 2.6 μmol/g (
FW
), respectively. The results show that 3-pentanol glycosides are abundantly distributed in root nodules, while they are distributed in leaves, roots and stems at low level. By contrast, 3-pentanol glycosides are not detected in fruits.
